17th June 2026

Had a bit of a reality check in today's lecture. I’ve been assuming market data is this pristine, flawless feed, but it turns out real-world data is incredibly messy. I need to build a data cleaner class immediately to handle a few glaring issues:
- The 'Zero' Trap: If the data drops out and throws a NaN mid-session, my current model would probably crash. Instead of being lazy and filling gaps with a zero, I'll use linear interpolation to estimate the missing prices smoothly.
- Anomaly Filtering: Sometimes stock prices just glitch. If an asset spikes 10% in a second and instantly reverts, my stop-losses will trigger for no reason. I definitely need a spike filter to detect and delete those dodgy ticks.


19th June 2026

Spent the afternoon untangling corporate actions. It sounds obvious now, but failing to clean historical data will completely break an algorithm.
- The "Split Problem": If a stock like Nvidia does a 4-for-1 split, the raw price drops by 75%. My model would read that as a catastrophic market crash! From now on, the algorithm will run strictly on the Adjusted Close price to account for splits and dividend drops accurately.
- Survivorship Bias: It is so tempting to just backtest on the current S&P 500 list. However, if I ignore all the companies that went bust or were delisted over the last decade, my strategy will look artificially brilliant. I have to include the failures in my testing universe.


21st June 2026

Fascinating end to the week looking at portfolio construction and market dynamics.
- Institutional vs. Retail: Seeing the sheer volume of institutional capital reinforced my decision to stick to highly liquid mega-caps. Institutions easily crush retail flow, so trading where liquidity is deepest is my best defence.
- Markowitz & Modern Portfolio Theory: The maths behind portfolio variance ($\sigma_p^2$) is elegant. It proves exactly how diversifying across un-correlated assets reduces overall risk.
- Avoiding P-Hacking: Calculating the optimal Sharpe ratio highlighted a massive trap—data spamming. It’s incredibly tempting to just blindly tweak parameters until the backtest curve looks like a straight line up. I have to stay disciplined. If a metric doesn't have a solid, mechanical reason for being there, I am not using it.
